829. diuites damnare atque domare, as a judge passing sentence on them and humbling their pride. Charmides was returning rich, therefore if Neptune had been true to his reputation he could not hope for mercy. But he found the reputation was not true, and therefore praises Neptune.

The fragment that follows v. 830 has no place here, for Charmides is not poor or a beggar, ‘ mendicis cur se adnumeret nulla causa.’
